const a = [
  {"id":4663,"text":"The portal vein is formed by the union of which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 488.","responses":[{"text":"The inferior mesenteric vein and the splenic vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The superior mesenteric vein and the inferior mesenteric vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The superior mesenteric vein and the splenic vein","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"The splenic vein and the inferior pancreaticoduodenal vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The inferior mesenteric vein and the inferior pancreaticoduodenal vein","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4691,"text":"Which of the following arteries provide the blood supply to the abdominal esophagus?","explanation":null,"reference":"Moore KL, Dalley AF, Agur AMR. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 6th ed. Wolters Kluwer Health/Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2010: 279.","responses":[{"text":"Thoracic aorta","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior thyroid artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left iliac artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Suprarenal artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left gastric artery","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4702,"text":"What is the rate-limiting enzyme of the urea cycle?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 256.","responses":[{"text":"Arginosuccinate lyase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ornithine synthase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carbamoyl phosphate synthetase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Arginosuccinate synthase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ornithine transcarbamylase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4762,"text":"Which statement is incorrect about gallbladder histology?","explanation":null,"reference":"Laiq Hussain Siddiqui. Medical Histology Text And Atlas. 6th ed. Paramount; 2019: 203-204.","responses":[{"text":"Nerves and blood vessels in submucosa","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Thin smooth muscle oriented diagonally","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"No muscularis mucosa and submucosa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epithelium with folds","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Perimuscular dense connective tissue","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4790,"text":"During swallowing, respiration is inhibited for a fraction of the respiratory cycle. Which stage is this?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 798-799.","responses":[{"text":"Pharyngeal voluntary phase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Esophageal phase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Esophageal involuntary phase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Voluntary phase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pharyngeal phase","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4877,"text":"Which of the following artery supplies blood to the pancreas?","explanation":"The pancreas receives its blood supply primarily from the **splenic artery**, a branch of the **celiac trunk**. The celiac trunk is a major branch of the abdominal aorta that supplies blood to various organs in the upper abdomen, including the liver, stomach, spleen, and pancreas.\r\n\r\nThe splenic artery courses along the upper border of the pancreas and then divides into multiple smaller branches within the pancreas itself. These branches form an intricate network of blood vessels that supply the various parts of the pancreas.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 491.","responses":[{"text":"Left gastric artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior esophageal artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cystic artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior mesenteric artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Splenic artery","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4954,"text":"Which of the following enzymes is responsible for cleaving off glucose-1-phosphate from the peripheral end of a long branch of glycogen during glycogenolysis?","explanation":"**Glycogen phosphorylase** is the enzyme responsible for cleaving off glucose-1-phosphate from the peripheral end of a long branch of glycogen during glycogenolysis. \r\n\r\nGlycogenolysis is the breakdown of glycogen into glucose to provide a rapid source of energy. The process involves the sequential removal of glucose molecules from the non-reducing ends of glycogen branches. Glycogen phosphorylase is a key enzyme involved in this process.\r\n\r\nWhen glycogen phosphorylase acts on the glycogen molecule, it cleaves glucose units from the outermost ends of the glycogen branches by catalyzing the following reaction:\r\n\r\nGlycogen + Phosphate → Glycogen (n-1) + Glucose-1-phosphate\r\n\r\nThis reaction results in the release of glucose-1-phosphate and a smaller glycogen molecule with one less glucose unit. The released glucose-1-phosphate can be further metabolized to provide energy or used for other metabolic processes.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 128.","responses":[{"text":"Branching enzyme","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glycogen synthase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Debranching enzyme","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucose-6-phosphatase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glycogen phosphorylase","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":5001,"text":"Which of the following is true regarding bile canaliculi?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 783.","responses":[{"text":"They are found in the gall bladder","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They only contain unconjugated bilirubin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They arise from the intercellular spaces between hepatocytes","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"They are the largest branches of the biliary tree","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They empty into bile ductules","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":5028,"text":"What are the permanent folds in the wall of the intestines, containing a core of submucosa called?","explanation":null,"reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2015: 314.","responses":[{"text":"Plicae","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Crypts","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Villi","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rugae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pits","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":6081,"text":"Which of the following correctly describes the glycemic index?","explanation":"The **glycemic index (GI)** is defined as the **ability of food to increase blood glucose levels** when compared to a reference carbohydrate, typically glucose or white bread. Foods with a high GI are rapidly digested and absorbed, leading to a quicker and larger increase in blood glucose levels, while foods with a low GI are digested and absorbed more slowly, resulting in a slower and smaller increase in blood glucose levels.","reference":"(1) Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 366.\r\n\r\n\r\n(2) Vlachos D, Malisova S, Lindberg FA, Karaniki G. Glycemic index (Gi) or glycemic load (Gl) and dietary interventions for optimizing postprandial hyperglycemia in patients with t2 diabetes: a review. Nutrients. Published May 27, 2020. Accessed August 7, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7352659/","responses":[{"text":"The ability of the liver to maintain blood glucose levels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The ability of food to increase blood glucose levels","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"The ability of the liver to increase blood glucose levels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The ability of the liver to reduce blood glucose levels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The ability of food to reduce blood glucose levels","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9360,"text":"Which of the following is the rate-limiting enzyme in cholesterol synthesis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 221.","responses":[{"text":"Mevalonate carboxylase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prenyl transferase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Squalene synthase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HMG-CoA synthase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HMG-CoA reductase","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":9431,"text":"Which of the following cells are not present in the small intestine?","explanation":null,"reference":"Dixon LJ, Barnes M, Tang H, Pritchard MT, Nagy LE. Kupffer cells in the liver. Comprehensive Physiology. Published April 2013. Accessed August 24, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4748178/","responses":[{"text":"Paneth cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Absorptive cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Microfold cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Kupffer cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Goblet cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9463,"text":"By which process do bile salts get absorbed in the terminal ileum?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 819.","responses":[{"text":"Facilitated diffusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Active transport","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"By binding with calbindin protein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Simple diffusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Osmosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9467,"text":"Zymogen granules from pancreatic acinar cells are released by which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":"Barrett KE, Brooks HL, Barman SM, Yuan JXJ. Ganong’s Review of Medical Physiology. 26th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2019: 452.","responses":[{"text":"Secretin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ghrelin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cholecystokinin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucose-dependant insulinotropic peptide (GIP)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastrin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9526,"text":"A 58-year-old male is diagnosed with diabetes. On multiple follow-up visits, his blood sugar levels are high despite reviewing his medication and ruling out any other causes for it. Upon detailed inquiry, the patient revealed that he takes his medication occasionally as he visits a faith healer who he believes will cure him and thinks daily medication is unnecessary. Which of the following should be the next step of management in this case?","explanation":"In this scenario, the patient's health beliefs are affecting his adherence to the recommended medical treatment. Understanding and addressing these beliefs is essential for effective management. Hence, the most appropriate next step in the management of this patient is to **counsel him, keeping in mind the health belief model**. \r\n\r\nThis model emphasizes understanding the patient's perceived susceptibility, severity, benefits of treatment, barriers to treatment, and cues to action. By utilizing this model, the healthcare provider can tailor the counseling to the patient's specific beliefs and concerns, hopefully leading to better adherence to the prescribed treatment regimen.","reference":"Dow Lecture slides: Gastrointestinal module, Subject: Behavioral sciences, Topic: Social Support, Treatment And Adherent Stigma, Sub-topic: Guidelines to improve adherence","responses":[{"text":"Admit him to the medical unit","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Advise him to bring a family member on his next visit","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Advise him to exercise daily","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Make a diet plan for him to follow","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Counsel him, keeping in mind the health belief model","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":9527,"text":"A distant relative comes to you for advice regarding her son. After listening to her, you conclude that her son might have schizophrenia. You recommend that she should visit a psychiatrist, to which she shows hesitation, stating that she cannot do that for it will bring disgrace to the family and people will make fun of them. Which of the following terms best defines the association of mental disorders with the fear of disgrace?","explanation":"The association of mental disorders with the fear of disgrace is best defined by the term **stigma**. Stigma refers to the **negative attitudes, beliefs, and stereotypes** that people have about individuals with certain traits or conditions, including mental disorders. It can lead to discrimination, exclusion, and other adverse outcomes for the affected individual and their families. The fear of being stigmatized can deter individuals from seeking help or treatment.","reference":"Dow Lecture slides: Gastrointestinal module, Subject: Behavioral sciences, Topic: Social Support, Treatment And Adherent Stigma, Sub-topic: What is STIGMA?","responses":[{"text":"Stigma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pessimism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Discrimination","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Disempowerment","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prejudice","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9529,"text":"Children raised with this parenting style can depend on their caregivers, show distress when separated, and joy when reunited. They tend to seek comfort and reassurance from their caregivers. Which parenting style is being referred to here?","explanation":"The parenting style being referred to here is the **secure attachment style**. Children with secure attachment feel confident that their caregivers will be available and responsive to their needs. They use their caregiver as a safe base from which to explore the world and seek them out for comfort during times of distress. Securely attached children display a balance of independence and attachment behaviors. \r\n\r\nAmbivalent, avoidant, and disorganized attachment styles are patterns of attachment that can arise in children due to inconsistent or inappropriate responses from caregivers. The permissive attachment style is not a recognized category of attachment; instead, \"permissive\" is a type of parenting style that is lenient and has few rules or boundaries.","reference":"Health (UK) NCC for M. Introduction to Children’s Attachment. National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE); 2015. Accessed September 2, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK356196/","responses":[{"text":"Secure attachment style","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Disorganized attachment style","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ambivalent attachment style","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Permissive attachment style","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Avoidant attachment style","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9530,"text":"A high-resolution transducer is used in the transluminal sonography of the gastrointestinal tract. For the esophagus, how many layers can normally be visualized?","explanation":"In high-resolution endoscopic ultrasonography (EUS) of the esophagus, **5 concentric layers** can normally be visualized. These layers correspond to various anatomical structures of the esophageal wall. \r\n\r\n**Endoscopic ultrasonography** is a valuable tool for evaluating the depth of invasion of tumors, detecting submucosal lesions, and assessing other pathological changes in the esophagus and nearby structures.","reference":"Dow Lecture slides: Gastrointestinal module, Subject: Radiology, Topic: Assessment of GIT (ultrasound), Sub-topic: Gastrointestinal wall layers.","responses":[{"text":"6 concentric layers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"5 concentric layers","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"2 concentric layers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"3 concentric layers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"4 concentric layers","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9531,"text":"A 45-year-old presents with a 1-week history of swelling in his right inguinal region, which appears on exertion and disappears on lying down. For the past 1 day, the swelling became painful and has since not gone away. On examination, it is now tense and tender. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"The presentation described is consistent with a **strangulated hernia**. The sudden onset of pain and the swelling becoming tense and tender suggest that the herniated bowel or tissue has lost its blood supply due to pressure on the blood vessels. This condition is a surgical emergency, as the lack of blood flow can quickly lead to gangrene and death of the involved tissue.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nAn obstructed hernia indicates that the bowel within the hernial sac has become obstructed, but it may still have an adequate blood supply.\r\n\r\nIndirect and direct inguinal hernias refer to the pathway the hernia takes through the abdominal wall. Indirect is through the inguinal canal and is more common in younger males, while direct is a protrusion through the posterior wall of the inguinal canal and is more common in older males.\r\n\r\nAn incarcerated hernia refers to a hernia that cannot be reduced (pushed back into the abdomen), but it does not necessarily indicate that the tissue inside is compromised in terms of blood supply.","reference":"Dow Lecture slides: Gastrointestinal module, Subject: Surgery, Topic: Hernia, Sub-topic: Complications of hernias","responses":[{"text":"Strangulated hernia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Direct inguinal hernia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Obstructed hernia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Incarcerated hernia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Indirect inguinal hernia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9532,"text":"Ascites secondary to an increase in hydrostatic pressure solely occur in which of the following diseases?","explanation":"**Ascites** secondary to an increase in hydrostatic pressure solely is most prominently seen in **cirrhosis**. In cirrhosis, **portal hypertension** leads to **increased hydrostatic pressure** in the hepatic sinusoids, pushing fluid out into the peritoneal cavity.\r\n\r\n\r\nNeoplasms can cause ascites due to obstruction of lymphatic vessels or by producing fluid, but it's not solely due to an increase in hydrostatic pressure.\r\n\r\nNephrotic syndrome leads to ascites primarily because of a reduction in oncotic pressure due to the loss of proteins in the urine, not solely because of increased hydrostatic pressure.\r\n\r\nInfections, such as peritonitis, cause ascites due to inflammation and increased capillary permeability, not just from hydrostatic pressure changes.\r\n\r\nConstrictive pericarditis does lead to increased hydrostatic pressure, but it affects the heart's ability to expand and fill during diastole, leading to increased venous pressures and eventually ascites.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 863.","responses":[{"text":"Cirrhosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Neoplasm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nephrotic syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Constructive pericarditis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Infection","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9533,"text":"When is the primary prophylaxis in spontaneous bacterial peritonitis indicated?","explanation":null,"reference":"Tsoris A, Marlar CA. Use of the child pugh score in liver disease. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed September 2, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK542308/","responses":[{"text":"Bilirubin \u003c 2.5 mg/dl","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ascites fluid protein \u003e 1.5 g/l","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Creatine \u003e 1.2 mg/dl","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serum Na \u003e 130 mg/l","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Child pugh score \u003e 9","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11033,"text":"Which of the following is the odd one out regarding Meckel's diverticulum?","explanation":"**Meckel's diverticulum** is located on the **anti-mesenteric border of the ileum**. It results from the incomplete obliteration of the vitelline duct during embryonic development and is indeed present in approximately 2% of the population. It can contain ectopic tissue, commonly gastric and pancreatic. It is sometimes referred to as an ileal diverticulum due to its location in the ileum.","reference":"Dow Lecture slides: Gastrointestinal module, Subject: Embryology, Topic: Development of midgut and hindgut, Sub-topic: Vitelline duct abnormalities","responses":[{"text":"It is present in 2% of the population","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It can function as ectopic pancreatic tissue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It forms on mesenteric side","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"It is due to a persistent vitelline duct","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is also called ileal diverticulum","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11409,"text":"A person presents to the emergency department with chronic diarrhea and abdominal pain for months. Findings show aphthous ulcers, deep linear fissures occupying the ascending and transverse colon but sparing the rectum and descending colon with skipped areas with excess fat creeping over mucosa. Cryptitis is also seen in lamina propria along with non-caseating granulomas. Which is the most probable diagnosis?","explanation":"The presentation includes chronic diarrhea and abdominal pain along with specific findings such as aphthous ulcers, deep linear fissures, and non-caseating granulomas in the lamina propria. These features are indicative of **Crohn's disease**. One of the hallmark characteristics of Crohn's is the presence of **\"skipped areas\"** of affected tissue, which contrasts with **ulcerative colitis** that usually shows continuous inflammation.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nLactose intolerance primarily causes diarrhea and bloating but does not lead to the aphthous ulcers, deep linear fissures, or non-caseating granulomas described in the question. Whipple disease is a systemic illness affecting multiple organs and is associated with a bacteria called *Tropheryma whipplei*; it would not specifically lead to the findings described.\r\n\r\nCeliac disease is an autoimmune disorder primarily affecting the small intestine in response to gluten intake and is characterized by villous atrophy rather than cryptitis and non-caseating granulomas.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 799.","responses":[{"text":"Celiac disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ulcerative colitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Whipple disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Crohn's disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lactose intolerance","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11429,"text":"Which of the following is due to the failure of the return of the physiological herniation of the gut in the yolk sac back into the abdominal cavity?","explanation":"**Omphalocele** is due to the **failure of the physiological herniation of the gut to return from the yolk sac** into the abdominal cavity during embryonic development. This results in the abdominal contents protruding through the umbilicus, covered by a translucent membrane.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nPersistence of vitelline duct is due to the failure of the vitelline duct to obliterate, but it is not related to the failure of physiological herniation of the gut into the yolk sac.\r\n\r\nGastroschisis is an abdominal wall defect where the intestines herniate through the wall, but it is not covered by a membrane. It is not due to the failure of physiological herniation of the gut into the yolk sac.\r\n\r\nMegacolon is usually due to Hirschsprung's disease, a congenital absence of ganglion cells in the colon.\r\n\r\nRetrocolic hernia is a type of abdominal hernia but is not related to the failure of physiological herniation of the gut into the yolk sac.","reference":"Sadler TW. Langman’s Medical Embryology. 14th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 100.","responses":[{"text":"Omphalocele","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Retrocolic hernia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Megacolon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Persistence of vitelline duct","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastroschisis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11431,"text":"Which of the following is the region having villi and submucosal glands?","explanation":"The **duodenum** is the specific region of the small intestine that has both **villi and submucosal glands (also known as Brunner's glands)**. The villi serve to increase the surface area for nutrient absorption, while the submucosal glands secrete an alkaline mucus that helps to neutralize stomach acid.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nThe jejunum and ileum have villi but lack submucosal glands.\r\n\r\nThe large intestine has neither villi nor submucosal glands.\r\n\r\nThe stomach has gastric glands but lacks villi.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2018: 317.","responses":[{"text":"Duodenum","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Jejunum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Large intestine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ileum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stomach","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12862,"text":"During a colonoscopy, the colon is examined for the cause of blood in the stool. Which of the following is not a characteristic feature of the structure observed?","explanation":null,"reference":"Laiq Hussain Siddiqui. Medical Histology Text And Atlas. 7th ed. Paramount; 2019: 192.","responses":[{"text":"Crypts of Lieberkuhn","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glands in the mucosa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Few villi","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Teniae coli","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Numerous goblet cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12863,"text":"Which of the following is not a tributary of the portal vein?","explanation":null,"reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 490.","responses":[{"text":"Left gastric vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cystic vein","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior pancreaticoduodenal vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior mesenteric vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Splenic vein","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12864,"text":"Filtered blood exits the liver via which of the following vessels/structures?","explanation":null,"reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 498.","responses":[{"text":"Cystic duct","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatic vein","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatic portal vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatic duct","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatic artery","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12866,"text":"Which of the following abdominal viscera is most vulnerable to trauma to 9-11 ribs on the left side of the body?","explanation":null,"reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 505.","responses":[{"text":"Gall bladder","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pancreas","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Appendix","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Kidney","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spleen","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12867,"text":"The pancreas is considered a retroperitoneal organ. Which part of this gland is intraperitoneal?","explanation":null,"reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 332.","responses":[{"text":"Head","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Uncinate process","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neck","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Body","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tail","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12868,"text":"A number of structures open (related) in the 2nd part of the duodenum. Which of the following does not have an opening in the duodenum?","explanation":"In the second part of the duodenum, several structures open or empty their contents. The duodenum is the first part of the small intestine and is responsible for receiving and digesting partially digested food from the stomach.\r\n\r\nThe structures that have openings in the second part of the duodenum include:\r\n\r\n1. **Bile Duct:** The bile duct carries bile from the liver and gallbladder to the duodenum, where bile aids in the digestion of fats.\r\n\r\n2. **Pancreatic Duct:** The main pancreatic duct delivers pancreatic enzymes and bicarbonate to the duodenum, assisting in the digestion of carbohydrates, proteins, and fats.\r\n\r\n3. **Accessory Pancreatic Duct:** The accessory pancreatic duct (Duct of Santorini) is an additional duct of the pancreas that may be present in some individuals. It opens into the duodenum at a more proximal location called the minor duodenal papilla.\r\n\r\n4. **Ampulla of Vater:** The ampulla of Vater is the confluence of the bile duct and pancreatic duct, and it opens into the second part of the duodenum through the major duodenal papilla. It allows both bile and pancreatic secretions to enter the duodenum.\r\n\r\nHowever, the **Cystic Duct** does not open into the duodenum. Instead, it connects the gallbladder to the common bile duct, allowing the gallbladder to store and concentrate bile.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 336.","responses":[{"text":"Ampulla of Vater","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pancreatic duct","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cystic duct","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Bile duct","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Accessory pancreatic duct","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12870,"text":"A second-year resident in surgery, while revising the anterior abdominal wall, noticed that the conjoint tendon resists the occurrence of an inguinal hernia. The tendon that resists the hernia is made of aponeurotic fibers from which of the following muscles?","explanation":null,"reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 425.","responses":[{"text":"External oblique and internal oblique","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Internal oblique and transversus abdominis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"External oblique and transversus abdominis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Internal oblique and rectus abdominis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"External oblique and rectus abdominis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12871,"text":"The second-year MBBS students studying stomach specimens noted lesser curvature. Incisura angularis represents the junction between which of the following anatomical locations?","explanation":null,"reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 455.","responses":[{"text":"Cardia and fundus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cardia and pyloric part of stomach","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Body and pyloric part of stomach","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Fundus and pyloric part of stomach","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cardia and body","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12872,"text":"A patient with chronic epigastric pain comes for a follow-up with a computed tomography scan report of the abdomen showing enlarged gastric nodes. Which of the following structures drains into it?","explanation":null,"reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 456.","responses":[{"text":"Superior 2/3rd of stomach","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Right 2/3rd of inferior 1/3rd of stomach","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pylorus of stomach","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Middle part of esophagus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left 1/3rd of greater curvature","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12873,"text":"A demonstrator while explaining lymphatic drainage of the stomach, tells students the relation of lymph nodes with the arteries. Which of the following lymph nodes are located along the short gastric and left gastro-omental arteries?","explanation":null,"reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 456.","responses":[{"text":"Pyloric","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior gastric","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior gastric","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pancreatico-duodenal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pancreatico-splenic","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12874,"text":"A patient, after the caesarian section, comes into the outpatient department with a complaint of a bulge in the midline of the anterior abdominal wall. After examination and investigation, a diagnosis of the separation of\r\nrectus abdominis due to weakened linea alba is made. Separated muscle is innervated by which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 410.","responses":[{"text":"T5 to T12","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"T3 to T7","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"T2 to T7","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"T3 to T11","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"T1 to T5","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12875,"text":"A house officer, while examining a child, notices that the stroking of skin on the medial aspect of the thigh results in reflex contraction and retraction of the testis. Which of the following muscles of the anterior abdominal wall is responsible for this reflex?","explanation":null,"reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 296.","responses":[{"text":"Rectus abdominis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transversus abdominis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pyramidalis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"External oblique","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cremaster","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12876,"text":"The reflected inguinal ligament receives fibers from the contralateral aponeurosis of which of the following structures?","explanation":null,"reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 425.","responses":[{"text":"Transverse abdominal oblique","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rectus abdominis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"External abdominal oblique","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Internal abdominal oblique","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pyramidalis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12877,"text":"A 60-year-old male presents in the surgical outpatient department with a complaint of swelling in his left groin. After examination, a diagnosis of a direct inguinal hernia is made. Which of the following fossae are potential sites for direct inguinal hernias?","explanation":null,"reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 438.","responses":[{"text":"Lateral inguinal fossa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medial inguinal fossa","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Supravesical fossa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Iliac fossa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ischiorectal fossa","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12879,"text":"A 60-year-old alcoholic male comes to the medical outpatient department with dilated veins in his abdominal region. He is diagnosed with caput medusae due to portal hypertension. Which of the following veins, when dilated, produces caput medusae?","explanation":null,"reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 504.","responses":[{"text":"Para-umbilical vein","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Splenic vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pancreatic vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cystic vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Proper hepatic vein","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12880,"text":"How are pelvic splanchnic nerves distinct from other splanchnic nerves?","explanation":null,"reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 530.","responses":[{"text":"Derived from ventral primary rami of L2, L3, L4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Provide postganglionic sympathetic innervation to the cecum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Convey preganglionic parasympathetic fibers to the inferior hypogastric plexus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Derived from the sympathetic trunks","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Convey postganglionic parasympathetic innervation to the ascending colon","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12882,"text":"In which of the following structures, hypertrophic pancreatic tissue can be seen?","explanation":null,"reference":"An J, Zabbo CP. Meckel diverticulum. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed December 4, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK499960/","responses":[{"text":"Anal canal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Jejunum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rectum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mouth","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Meckel's diverticulum","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12883,"text":"A histological section is being observed showing a serous gland of compound tubulo-acinar variety. The secretory unit consists of pyramidal serous cells and specialized pale, low cuboidal epithelial cells. Numerous spherical cell clusters are also scattered. Which of the following structures is being observed?","explanation":null,"reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2015: 332-333.","responses":[{"text":"Submandibular","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pancreas","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sublingual","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Parotid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Duodenum","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12884,"text":"Choose the correct option regarding the derivative of hepatic bud.","explanation":null,"reference":"(1) Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2016: 217.\r\n\r\n(2) Lalor P, Lai W, Curbishley S, Shetty S, Adams D. Human hepatic sinusoidal endothelial cells can be distinguished by expression of phenotypic markers related to their specialised functions in vivo. World Journal of Gastroenterology : WJG. Published September 14, 2006. Accessed December 10, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4088223/","responses":[{"text":"Hepatic sinusoids","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemopoietic cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stroma of liver","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Kupffer cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Parenchyma of liver","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12885,"text":"Select the incorrect option regarding derivatives of dorsal pancreatic bud.","explanation":null,"reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2016: 219.","responses":[{"text":"Entire main pancreatic duct","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Head (upper part)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tail","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Body","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neck","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12887,"text":"A newborn's failure to pass meconium within the first 24 hours after birth may indicate which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 109.","responses":[{"text":"Intestinal malrotation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tracheoesophageal fistula","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hirschsprung disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Esophageal atresia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Duodenal atresia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12969,"text":"A 1-day-old newborn with a history of bilious vomiting. The baby's physical examination is normal. There is a history of polyhydramnios during pregnancy. An abdominal X-ray shows a double bubble gas shadow. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2016: 215-216.","responses":[{"text":"Midgut volvulus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pyloric stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Duodenal atresia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Imperforate anus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Esophageal atresia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12970,"text":"A neonate presents with persistent vomiting and respiratory distress. A trachea-esophageal fistula (TEF) is suspected. What is the most common type of this fistula?","explanation":null,"reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2016: 198.","responses":[{"text":"Esophageal atresia with a proximal TEF","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Esophageal atresia with double TEF","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Esophageal atresia with distal TEF","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pure esophageal atresia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Isolated TEF","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12971,"text":"Which of the following effects is produced in the gastrointestinal tract by the stimulation of the parasympathetic nerves?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 769.","responses":[{"text":"Increase in absorption of nutrients","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibition of secretion from the stomach","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibition of intestinal secretions","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Contraction of sphincters","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increase in motility and tone","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12972,"text":"Secretion of gastrin hormone is increased by which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":"(1) Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 813.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n(2) Le T, Vikas Bhushan. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2021. 31st ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2021: 381.","responses":[{"text":"Low pH of gastric juice","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vasoactive intestinal peptide (VIP)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Somatostatin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastric inhibitory peptide (GIP)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Products of protein digestion","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12976,"text":"Which of the following mechanisms causes maximum gastric acid secretion?","explanation":null,"reference":"(1) Stomach acid secretion - an overview | sciencedirect topics. Accessed December 10, 2022. https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/medicine-and-dentistry/stomach-acid-secretion\r\n\r\n(2) Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 813.","responses":[{"text":"H2 receptor stimulation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neurogenic stimulation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cholinergic receptor stimulation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibition of acetylcholine release","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Na/K ATPase pump stimulation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12977,"text":"Which of the following inhibits gastric acid secretion by action on the parietal cell?","explanation":null,"reference":"(1) Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 812.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n(2) Le T, Vikas Bhushan. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2021. 31st ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2021: 382.","responses":[{"text":"Histamine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acetylcholine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastrin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epinephrine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prostaglandin E","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12978,"text":"Hepcidin prevents the absorption of which of the following substances from the small intestine, thus preventing its accumulation in the blood?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 404.","responses":[{"text":"Vitamin B12","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Folate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Magnesium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Copper","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Iron","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12979,"text":"The monosaccharide fructose is absorbed into the intestinal epithelial cells with the help of which of the following transport proteins?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 831.","responses":[{"text":"GLUT4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"SGLT1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"SGLT2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"GLUT5","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"GLUT2","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12981,"text":"Which type of electrical and motor activity in the gastrointestinal tract occurs during periods of fasting?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 792-793.","responses":[{"text":"Migratory motility complex","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Segmentation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Peristalsis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Slow wave complex","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Basic electrical rhythm","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12982,"text":"Which of the following is a biochemical reaction that occurs in gluconeogenesis but not in glycolysis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 118-121.","responses":[{"text":"Conversion of fructose-6-phosphate to fructose-1,6-bisphosphate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Conversion of dihydroxyacetone to glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Conversion of fumarate into malate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Conversion of glucose to glucose-6-phosphate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Conversion of pyruvate to phosphoenolpyruvate","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12984,"text":"A 40-year-old man is admitted to a local hospital. He has a 102°F temperature along with abdominal pain. His skin color is pale and he has diarrhea. His liver enzymes are in high ranges. Which liver enzyme may be elevated in his condition?","explanation":null,"reference":"(1) Lala V, Zubair M, Minter DA. Liver function tests. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed December 8, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482489/\r\n\r\n\r\n(2) Kalaitzakis E. Gastrointestinal dysfunction in liver cirrhosis. World Journal of Gastroenterology : WJG. Published October 28, 2014. Accessed December 8, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4209534/\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n(3) Detail. Accessed December 8, 2022. https://www.who.int/news-room/fact-sheets/detail","responses":[{"text":"Lactate carboxylase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glutamate kinase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Creatinine kinase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alanine aminotransferase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Aspartate dehydrogenase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12985,"text":"During electron transport, a pair of electrons is accepted from NADH by which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 74-75.","responses":[{"text":"NADH-coenzyme Q reductase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cytochrome c oxidase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Succinate-coenzyme Q reductase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Coenzyme Q-succinate reductase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Coenzyme Q-cytochrome c reductase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12986,"text":"Chemosmotic theory for oxidative phosphorylation proposes ATP generation via which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 77.","responses":[{"text":"Glycolysis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Beta-oxidation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"NADH+ transport","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Proton gradient","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ca+ concentration","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12987,"text":"Which of the following is an enzyme of the glycolysis pathway that is activated due to low levels of cellular ATP?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 99.","responses":[{"text":"Isomerase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pyruvate kinase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hexokinase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phosphofructokinase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucokinase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12988,"text":"Where are the enzymes of the tricarboxylic acid (TCA cycle) in a eukaryotic cell located?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 109.","responses":[{"text":"Nucleus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endoplasmic reticulum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasma membrane","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lysosomal bodies","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mitochondria","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12989,"text":"A 35-year-old female patient comes to the outpatient department with a complaint of abdominal pain, dark urine, itchy skin, and fatigue. Her labs show total bilirubin 8.5 mg/dl (0.1-1. mg/dl), SGOT 99 U/L (40-129 U/L), SGPT 39 U/L (8-48 U/L), alkaline phosphatase 305 U/L (40-129 U/L) and gamma GT 166 U/L (8-61 U/L). Which of the following is this patient suffering from?","explanation":null,"reference":"Lala V, Zubair M, Minter DA. Liver function tests. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed December 8, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482489/","responses":[{"text":"Hemolytic jaundice","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatitis B infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Obstructive jaundice","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatic jaundice","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatocellular carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12990,"text":"Hepatic encephalopathy is due to which of the following?","explanation":"The correct answer is **accumulation of glutamine and glutamate**.\r\n\r\nHepatic encephalopathy is a neurological condition associated with liver dysfunction. In liver failure, the liver's ability to detoxify ammonia is compromised. Ammonia accumulates in the blood and crosses the blood-brain barrier, where it interferes with neurotransmitter function and causes neurological symptoms. Astrocytes in the brain convert excessive ammonia to glutamine through the enzyme glutamine synthetase. While this is usually a protective mechanism, in the context of hepatic encephalopathy, the overproduction of glutamine leads to osmotic imbalance, resulting in cerebral edema and increased intracranial pressure. This accumulation of glutamine and glutamate in brain tissue is responsible for the neurologic manifestations seen in hepatic encephalopathy.","reference":"(1) Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 256.\r\n(2) Ali R, Nagalli S. Hyperammonemia. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed December 10, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557504/","responses":[{"text":"Accumulation of colonic bacteria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Accumulation of glutamine and glutamate","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Accumulation of urea in brain tissues","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Extensive muscle degradation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Excessive metabolism of dietary protein","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12992,"text":"Digestion of which one of the following does not begin in the mouth?","explanation":"Digestion of **proteins** does not begin in the mouth. In contrast, digestion of carbohydrates like amylose and amylopectin commences in the oral cavity with the enzymatic action of salivary amylase. Salivary amylase starts breaking down complex carbohydrates into simpler sugars. Lipids also start to undergo some level of digestion in the mouth through the enzyme lingual lipase, secreted by the lingual glands located at the base of the tongue. However, protein digestion is initiated in the stomach, where the gastric glands secrete pepsinogen, which gets converted into the active enzyme pepsin in the acidic environment. Pepsin begins the process of protein hydrolysis, breaking down proteins into smaller peptides.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 247.","responses":[{"text":"Amylopectin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Complex carbohydrates","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amylose","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Proteins","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lipids","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12993,"text":"Storage of vitamin B12 is one of the functions of the liver related to which of the following?","explanation":"Vitamin B12 (cobalamin) plays a crucial role in various physiological processes, but it is particularly vital for **blood formation**, or hematopoiesis. Specifically, vitamin B12 is essential for the maturation of red blood cells in the bone marrow, and it is a co-factor for the enzyme methionine synthase, which is necessary for the synthesis of DNA. A deficiency in vitamin B12 can lead to megaloblastic anemia, a condition characterized by the production of abnormally large and immature red blood cells. The liver acts as the primary storage site for vitamin B12, storing enough of this vitamin to last several years. By storing vitamin B12, the liver ensures that a constant supply is available for processes like blood formation, thereby maintaining hematopoietic integrity.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 378-380.","responses":[{"text":"Immunity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blood formation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Synthesis of plasma proteins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Deamination of amino acids","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Detoxification of various substances","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13043,"text":"Which of the following metabolic pathways maintain blood glucose concentration during fasting?","explanation":"During fasting, the body needs to maintain blood glucose levels to supply energy to tissues like the brain that are highly dependent on glucose. **Liver glycogenolysis** is the process by which glycogen stored in the liver is broken down into glucose and released into the bloodstream. This process is catalyzed by the enzyme glycogen phosphorylase, which is activated by glucagon, a hormone released by the pancreas during periods of low blood sugar. Unlike muscle glycogen, liver glycogen can be used to increase blood glucose levels, as liver cells possess the enzyme glucose-6-phosphatase that allows for the dephosphorylation of glucose-6-phosphate to free glucose, which can then be released into the bloodstream. Therefore, liver glycogenolysis is critical for maintaining blood glucose levels during fasting.","reference":"Sanvictores T, Casale J, Huecker MR. Physiology, fasting. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed December 3, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK534877/","responses":[{"text":"Liver glycogenolysis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Erythrocyte glycolysis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Muscles glycogenesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hexose monophosphate shunt (HMS)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tricarboxylic acid (TCA) cycle","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13044,"text":"While assessing obesity in women, an android type is defined by which of the following waist-to-hip ratio?","explanation":"In assessing obesity, an android or \"apple-shaped\" distribution of body fat is defined by a waist-to-hip ratio of **more than 0.8** in women. This type of fat distribution is associated with a higher risk of metabolic syndrome, cardiovascular diseases, and type 2 diabetes. The android pattern is characterized by the accumulation of fat primarily in the abdominal area and is considered more metabolically active. It is more likely to lead to conditions such as insulin resistance due to the release of free fatty acids into the portal circulation, which directly affects liver metabolism. On the other hand, a \"gynoid\" or \"pear-shaped\" distribution, defined by a waist-to-hip ratio of less than 0.8, is considered less risky as fat is mainly distributed around the hips and thighs.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 350.","responses":[{"text":"Less than 0.8","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"More than 0.8","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Less than 1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Equal to 1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"More than 1","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13045,"text":"Upper body obesity is linked with higher health risks because of which of the following characteristics of adipose deposits?","explanation":"Upper body or abdominal obesity is considered more hazardous to health primarily because adipose tissue in this area **releases free fatty acids directly into the portal vein**. The portal vein supplies the liver, which is a central organ in metabolism. Increased levels of free fatty acids in the liver contribute to insulin resistance, a key factor in the development of type 2 diabetes and cardiovascular disease. Insulin resistance can lead to increased glucose production by the liver and impaired fat storage, elevating levels of circulating lipids and further contributing to cardiovascular risk. In contrast, lower body obesity does not have this direct pathway to the liver, making it relatively less risky in terms of metabolic and cardiovascular complications.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 350.","responses":[{"text":"Anatomically close to heart","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Utilized for energy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Deposited in muscles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Release free fatty acids into portal vein","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Encapsulate liver","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13046,"text":"Which of the following changes occur in fat cells during voluntary weight loss?","explanation":"The correct answer is **Number is not affected**.\r\n\r\n1. **Cell Size Reduction**: During voluntary weight loss, the fat cells shrink in size due to the breakdown of stored triglycerides, but their number remains unchanged.\r\n\r\n2. **No Programmed Cell Death**: There is no significant programmed cell death (apoptosis) of adipocytes during voluntary weight loss.\r\n\r\n3. **No Hyperplasia**: Hyperplasia, or an increase in the number of cells, is not observed in this scenario.\r\n\r\n4. **No Reaccumulation**: The cells may reaccumulate fat if caloric intake increases again, but this is not a direct result of voluntary weight loss.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 351.","responses":[{"text":"Number is not affected","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Reaccumulates fat","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Programmed cell death","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Size is not reduced","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperplasia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13048,"text":"Which of the following is a chemical factor released from the stomach that influences food intake and physical activity?","explanation":"The chemical factor released from the stomach that influences food intake and physical activity is **Ghrelin**.\r\nThe role of ghrelin is as follows:\r\n\r\n1. **Appetite Regulation**: Ghrelin is often termed the \"hunger hormone.\" It is secreted when the stomach is empty and stimulates the appetite, encouraging food intake.\r\n  \r\n2. **Metabolic Functions**: It also plays a role in preparing the body for incoming nutrients and influences carbohydrate and lipid metabolism.\r\n\r\n3. **Physical Activity**: Some studies indicate that ghrelin might also play a part in triggering physical activity, although this is less understood.\r\n\r\nIncorrect options:\r\n**Insulin**: Secreted by the pancreas, primarily regulates glucose metabolism.\r\n**Serotonin**: A neurotransmitter involved in mood regulation, among other functions.\r\n**Leptin**: Produced by adipose tissue, it signals satiety and inhibits food intake.\r\n**Dopamine**: A neurotransmitter mainly involved in reward and pleasure pathways.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 880.","responses":[{"text":"Leptin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Insulin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serotonin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dopamine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ghrelin","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13085,"text":"A 40-year-old woman has had increasing abdominal girth for a month, and pain for the past few days. On physical examination, there is hepatomegaly and caput medusae. Laboratory studies show hemoglobin 20.5 g/dL, hematocrit 61.7%, platelet count 411,000/mm3, aspartate transaminase (AST) 333 U/L, and alanine transaminase (ALT) 358 U/L. What is ultrasonography of her abdomen most likely to show?","explanation":"The condition most likely to be shown on ultrasonography given the patient's symptoms and laboratory findings is **Hepatic Vein Thrombosis**, also known as Budd-Chiari syndrome.\r\n\r\n- **Increasing abdominal girth** and **pain**: Indicates fluid accumulation and liver congestion.\r\n- **Hepatomegaly and caput medusae**: Signs of portal hypertension.\r\n- **High hemoglobin and hematocrit**: Possibly secondary to dehydration or increased erythropoiesis due to chronic hypoxia.\r\n- **Elevated AST and ALT**: Liver damage.\r\n\r\nThese clinical findings point toward hepatic vein thrombosis which leads to impaired blood outflow from the liver, causing hepatomegaly, portal hypertension, and elevated liver enzymes.\r\n\r\n**Hepatocellular carcinoma**: Lacks specific symptoms presented in this scenario.\r\n**Choledocholithiasis**: Wouldn't produce these blood test results or caput medusae.\r\n**Macrovesicular steatosis**: ALT and AST would be mildly elevated, and no hepatomegaly or caput medusae.\r\n**Cirrhosis**: Typically has more insidious onset and would have more chronic changes in liver function tests.","reference":"(1) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 829-830, 863.Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 829-830, 863.\r\n\r\n(2) Pillai AA, Fazal S, Babiker HM. Polycythemia. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed December 10, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK526081/","responses":[{"text":"Macrovesicular steatosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatocellular carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatic vein thrombosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Choledocholithiasis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cirrhosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13088,"text":"Barrett esophagus is a serious, long-term complication of chronic gastroesophageal reflux. Which of the following conditions is diagnostic for Barrett esophagus?","explanation":"In Barrett esophagus, the normal squamous epithelium of the lower esophagus undergoes **metaplasia** and transforms into columnar epithelium resembling intestinal mucosa. This change is considered pre-malignant and increases the risk for the development of esophageal adenocarcinoma. \r\n\r\n**Squamous dysplasia**: This is a pre-malignant condition involving squamous cells but is not specifically indicative of Barrett esophagus.\r\n**Intestinal dysplasia**: Dysplasia signifies a further step toward malignancy but is not diagnostic for Barrett esophagus per se.\r\n**Squamous metaplasia**: This involves a change from one type of squamous cell to another and is not characteristic of Barrett esophagus.\r\n**Gastric gland metaplasia**: While Barrett esophagus is associated with changes resembling gastric glands, the diagnostic feature is intestinal metaplasia.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 757.","responses":[{"text":"Gastric gland metaplasia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Squamous dysplasia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intestinal dysplasia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Squamous metaplasia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intestinal metaplasia","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13090,"text":"Which of the following is true regarding hepatitis C virus (HCV) infection?","explanation":"The true statement regarding Hepatitis C virus (HCV) infection is that it involves **Episodic elevations of serum aminotransferase levels**.\r\n\r\nHCV infection often leads to fluctuating levels of liver enzymes like alanine aminotransferase (ALT) and aspartate aminotransferase (AST). These episodic elevations correlate with cycles of liver cell injury and are used as markers for the disease's activity.\r\n\r\n**Anti-HCV antibody is protective against subsequent infections**: Anti-HCV antibodies are not protective and don't confer immunity.\r\n**Viral RNA disappears when anti-HCV appears in the blood**: The presence of anti-HCV antibodies doesn't necessarily mean that viral RNA will disappear.\r\n**Being an RNA virus, vertical transmission is not possible**: HCV, although an RNA virus, can still be vertically transmitted from mother to child.\r\n**Increased levels of anti-HCV antibodies confer effective immunity**: Anti-HCV antibodies do not provide immunity against the virus.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 834.","responses":[{"text":"Viral RNA disappears when anti-HCV appears in the blood","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anti-HCV antibody is protective against subsequent infections","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased levels of anti-HCV antibodies confer effective immunity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Episodic elevations of serum aminotransferase levels","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Being an RNA virus, vertical transmission is not possible","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13092,"text":"Which of the following conditions is true regarding the presence of antibodies against hepatitis B surface antigen in blood?","explanation":"The presence of antibodies against hepatitis B surface antigen (anti-HBs) in the blood **Indicates a complete recovery or immunity**.\r\n\r\nAnti-HBs antibodies generally appear after the disappearance of HBsAg and signal either recovery from an acute HBV infection or successful vaccination against HBV. These antibodies neutralize the virus, preventing future infections. In the clinical context, the presence of anti-HBs is a positive indicator of immunity against the virus, whether achieved through natural infection or through vaccination.\r\n\r\n**It is detectable after HBsAg disappears**: While true, this does not encompass the full range of conditions in which anti-HBs appear.\r\n**Helps to distinguish acute from chronic infection**: Anti-HBs typically do not appear in chronic infection.\r\n**Indicates immunity after inoculation with HBV vaccine**: True, but incomplete as it also occurs post-natural infection.\r\n**Indicates current or previous infection**: Presence of anti-HBs without HBsAg usually indicates past infection and recovery.","reference":"(1) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 832-833. \r\n\r\n(2) Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 120.","responses":[{"text":"Indicates a complete recovery or immunity","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"It is detectable after HBsAg disappears","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Indicates immunity after inoculation with HBV vaccine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Indicates current or previous infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Helps to distinguish acute from chronic infection","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13094,"text":"A 45-year-old man with long-standing gastroesophageal reflux undergoes upper gastrointestinal endoscopy that reveals patchy areas of epithelium resembling gastric mucosa extending 5 cm proximal to the esophagogastric junction. Biopsies are obtained. The pathological report describes \"Barrett esophagus\". Which of the following processes does this finding represent?","explanation":"The pathological finding of \"Barrett esophagus\" represents **Metaplasia**.\r\n\r\nIn Barrett esophagus, the normal stratified squamous epithelium of the esophagus is replaced by columnar epithelium that resembles gastric or intestinal mucosa. This change is a result of chronic gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD), where the esophageal mucosa is continually exposed to acidic gastric contents. Metaplasia is an adaptive response to this stress, as columnar epithelium is better suited to withstand the acidic environment compared to squamous epithelium. However, it carries a heightened risk for the development of adenocarcinoma of the esophagus.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 757.","responses":[{"text":"Metaplasia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertrophy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carcinoma in situ","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperplasia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atrophy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13101,"text":"What is the cause of nonspecific bacterial sialadenitis, frequently involving submandibular glands?","explanation":"**Staphylococcus aureus** is a Gram-positive bacterium that commonly colonizes the skin and mucous membranes. It is a leading cause of bacterial infections, including sialadenitis. Sialadenitis is often seen in the setting of salivary stasis, such as with salivary gland stones or reduced salivary flow, which creates a conducive environment for bacterial growth. The submandibular gland is most frequently affected due to its longer duct and the consistency of its saliva.\r\n\r\n**Streptococcus salivarius**: Normally found in the oral cavity but less commonly implicated.\r\n**Staphylococcus saprophyticus**: Rarely causes sialadenitis.\r\n**Streptococcus mutans**: Associated more with dental caries.\r\n**Staphylococcus epidermidis**: A skin commensal, less likely to cause sialadenitis compared to S. aureus.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 743.","responses":[{"text":"Staphylococcus epidermidis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Staphylococcus aureus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Streptococcus salivarius","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Staphylococcus saprophyticus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Streptococcus mutans","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13102,"text":"What is the most common tumor of the parotid gland?","explanation":"**Pleomorphic adenomas** are benign mixed tumors that are the most frequently occurring neoplasms of the salivary glands, particularly the parotid gland. These tumors are characterized histologically by a mixture of epithelial and mesenchymal elements. The \"pleomorphic\" nature refers to the variability in cell types, not to cellular pleomorphism, which usually signifies malignancy.\r\n\r\n**Oncocytoma**: Less common and typically occur in older adults.\r\n**Basal cell adenoma**: Also less common compared to pleomorphic adenoma.\r\n**Adenoid cystic carcinoma**: A malignant salivary gland tumor, not as common as pleomorphic adenoma.\r\n**Warthin tumor**: The second most common benign parotid tumor, usually occurs in older males who smoke.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 744.","responses":[{"text":"Pleomorphic adenoma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Warthin tumor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adenoid cystic carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oncocytoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Basal cell adenoma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13103,"text":"The biopsy specimen taken from the stomach shows a superficial mucosal defect and mucosal neutrophilic infiltrate. Which term best describes the features?","explanation":"In **acute gastritis**, the histological hallmarks include neutrophilic infiltrate within the gastric mucosa and superficial mucosal defects. Unlike chronic gastritis, where a lymphocytic infiltrate is more common, acute gastritis shows a rapid onset of inflammation, predominantly with neutrophils. The presence of a superficial mucosal defect also suggests the acute nature of the lesion, as opposed to deeper, more chronic ulcerations found in conditions like peptic ulcers.\r\n\r\n**Chronic gastritis**: Characterized by lymphocytic infiltrates and glandular atrophy.\r\n**Hemorrhagic gastritis**: Would exhibit bleeding in the gastric wall.\r\n**Gastric erosion**: While similar, this term doesn't capture the inflammatory component.\r\n**Peptic ulcer**: Typically deeper and involves both mucosa and submucosa, may even reach muscularis propria.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 760.","responses":[{"text":"Peptic ulcer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastric erosion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute gastritis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemorrhagic gastritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic gastritis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13104,"text":"Which one of the following is unlikely to be the morphological feature of Helicobacter\r\npylori gastritis?","explanation":"The morphological feature that is unlikely to be associated with Helicobacter pylori gastritis is **Increased parietal cell mass and acid secretion**.\r\n\r\nHelicobacter pylori gastritis primarily affects the antral mucosa, leading to a localized inflammatory response. The bacterium tends to inhibit somatostatin release, which would normally decrease gastrin secretion. Elevated gastrin levels may initially stimulate acid secretion, but in chronic cases, the infection often progresses to involve the body of the stomach, leading to mucosal atrophy and a reduction in acid-secreting parietal cells. Thus, increased parietal cell mass and acid secretion is generally not a long-term feature of H. pylori gastritis.\r\n\r\n**Increased risk of adenocarcinoma**: True, as H. pylori is classified as a Group 1 carcinogen.\r\n**Intestinal metaplasia**: Also true, and it is a precursor for gastric cancer.\r\n**Mucosal atrophy**: True, and it decreases acid output.\r\n**Present as antral gastritis**: True, it most often starts in the antrum.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 763-764.","responses":[{"text":"Present as antral gastritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased parietal cell mass and acid secretion","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Mucosal atrophy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased risk of adenocarcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intestinal metaplasia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13105,"text":"Which one of the following is a reversible hepatic response to injury?","explanation":"In **cholestasis**, there is an impairment of bile flow, leading to the accumulation of bile salts within the hepatocytes. It is a functional derangement that can be reversed if the underlying cause is identified and treated. The liver has a considerable capacity to regenerate, and bile flow can return to normal once the obstructive or inflammatory condition is resolved.\r\n\r\n**Fibrosis (stellate cells)**: This involves the deposition of extracellular matrix proteins and is generally irreversible.\r\n**Hepatocyte apoptosis**: Programmed cell death, generally irreversible.\r\n**Cirrhosis**: A late stage of scarring (fibrosis) of the liver, irreversible.\r\n**Hepatocyte necrosis**: Cell death, irreversible once it occurs.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 822.","responses":[{"text":"Hepatocyte necrosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrosis (stellate cells)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatocyte apoptosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cholestasis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cirrhosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13106,"text":"What is the doctor's ability to understand another person's culture, demonstrate knowledge of it and accept and respect the difference between his/her culture and clients' known as?","explanation":"**Cultural competence** goes beyond simply being aware of cultural differences; it encompasses the ability to effectively interact, communicate, and provide healthcare that considers the cultural context and specific needs of the client. It involves both cognitive and practical skills that are necessary for cultural adaptability and effectiveness in medical practice.\r\n\r\n**Cultural Sensitivity**: This is more about being considerate and respectful of differences but may not include a deep understanding or ability to interact effectively.\r\n**Cultural Motivation**: This term does not specifically describe the skill set involved in understanding and interacting with diverse cultures.\r\n**Cultural Awareness**: While important, awareness alone doesn't necessarily translate to competent practice.\r\n**Cultural Difference**: This is a general term that acknowledges differences between cultures but doesn't address the skill set involved in navigating these differences.","reference":"Dow Lecture slides: Gastrointestinal module, Subject: Behavioral sciences, Topic: Delivery of culturally relevant care and culture sensitivity, Sub-topic: Cultural competence.","responses":[{"text":"Cultural difference","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cultural awareness","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cultural competence","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cultural motivation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cultural sensitivity","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13109,"text":"Which of the following is a structure involved in the formation of the stomach bed?","explanation":"The **transverse mesocolon** is a peritoneal fold that attaches the transverse colon to the posterior abdominal wall. The stomach bed is formed by several structures that lie posterior to the stomach, and one of these is the transverse mesocolon. The stomach bed serves as the anatomical space against which the stomach rests and has its impressions.\r\n\r\n**Right Kidney**: Located more inferiorly and laterally, not directly forming the stomach bed.\r\n**Right Adrenal Gland**: Also more lateral, not directly forming the stomach bed.\r\n**Right Dome of Diaphragm**: Located superiorly, not directly involved in the formation of the stomach bed.\r\n**Duodenojejunal Flexure**: Located inferiorly, not involved in the stomach bed formation.","reference":"Dow Lecture slides: Gastrointestinal module, Subject: Anatomy, Topic: Esophagus (Abdominal Part) and Stomach, Sub-topic: Stomach bed","responses":[{"text":"Duodenojejunal flexure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right kidney","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transverse mesocolon","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Right dome of diaphragm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right adrenal gland","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13112,"text":"Which of the following neurohormones/neurotransmitters stimulate gastric acid secretion?","explanation":"**Histamine** acts on H2 receptors located on the parietal cells in the stomach lining, leading to an increase in cyclic AMP (cAMP), which in turn activates proton pumps and results in enhanced secretion of hydrochloric acid (HCl). Histamine generally works in synergy with gastrin and acetylcholine to regulate gastric acid output. It is a significant player in the triple mechanism that regulates acid release, and H2 receptor antagonists like ranitidine are used to inhibit this action to reduce acid secretion.\r\n\r\n**Serotonin**: Primarily involved in gastric motility.\r\n**Glycine**: An inhibitory neurotransmitter in the CNS, not involved in gastric acid secretion.\r\n**Dopamine**: Generally inhibits gastric acid secretion.\r\n**Glutamine**: An amino acid, not involved in direct regulation of gastric acid secretion.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 812.","responses":[{"text":"Histamine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Glycine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serotonin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dopamine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glutamine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13113,"text":"Vagally mediated increase in gastric acid secretion is partially mediated by which of the\r\nfollowing?","explanation":"The vagally mediated increase in gastric acid secretion is partially mediated by **Gastrin Releasing Peptide (GRP)**.\r\n\r\nWhen the vagus nerve stimulates the G-cells in the stomach, it primarily uses GRP as the neurotransmitter. This, in turn, leads to the release of gastrin, which stimulates the parietal cells to produce hydrochloric acid (HCl). The pathway essentially involves a two-step process: vagus nerve activation leads to GRP release, which then induces gastrin secretion for gastric acid production.\r\n\r\n**Vasoactive Intestinal Polypeptide (VIP)**: Generally inhibitory on gastric acid secretion.\r\n**Atropine**: A muscarinic receptor antagonist, would inhibit vagal stimulation.\r\n**Somatostatin**: Inhibits gastric acid secretion by acting on parietal cells.\r\n**Gastric Inhibitory Peptide (GIP)**: Its main effect is to decrease stomach acid secretion.","reference":"Le T, Vikas Bhushan. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2021. 31st ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2021: 381.","responses":[{"text":"Gastrin releasing peptide (GRP)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastric inhibitory peptide (GIP)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atropine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vasoactive intestinal polypeptide (VIP)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Somatostatin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13115,"text":"HCI is part of gastric secretion but its excessive secretion may lead to peptic ulcer. Hydrogen ion secretion by parietal cells occurs through which of the following pumps?","explanation":"The secretion of hydrogen ions by parietal cells in the stomach occurs through the **Hydrogen-Potassium ATPase** pump, also known as the H+/K+ ATPase pump.\r\n\r\nThis proton pump is located on the luminal surface of the gastric parietal cells and actively exchanges potassium ions (K+) from the gastric lumen for hydrogen ions (H+) from the cytoplasm. This is the final step in the secretion of hydrochloric acid (HCl) into the stomach. The process is energy-dependent and requires ATP. Inhibition of this pump by drugs like proton pump inhibitors (PPIs) is a key strategy in the management of conditions like peptic ulcers and gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD).\r\n\r\n**Hydrogen-calcium ATPase**: Not involved in gastric acid secretion.\r\n**Hydrogen-chloride ATPase**: Does not exist as a specific pump for this function.\r\n**Sodium-potassium ATPase**: Present in many cells but not involved in gastric acid secretion.\r\n**Sodium-hydrogen ATPase**: Involved in other ion transport mechanisms, not in gastric acid secretion.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 812.","responses":[{"text":"Hydrogen-calcium ATPase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hydrogen-chloride ATPase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sodium-hydrogen ATPase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sodium-potassium ATPase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hydrogen-potassium ATPase","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13117,"text":"Which of the following artery supplies blood to the lesser curvature of the stomach?","explanation":"The artery that supplies blood to the lesser curvature of the stomach is the **Left gastric artery**.\r\n\r\nThe left gastric artery arises from the celiac trunk and primarily supplies the lesser curvature of the stomach, along with contributing branches to the lower part of the esophagus. It may give off esophageal branches as well. An ulcer along the lesser curvature would therefore be in close proximity to this artery, making it a key vessel to be considered in the risk of gastrointestinal bleeding related to gastric ulcers.\r\n\r\n**Right gastro-omental artery**: Supplies the greater curvature of the stomach.\r\n**Posterior gastric artery**: Not a standard anatomical term for gastric arterial supply.\r\n**Gastroduodenal artery**: Supplies the pyloric region of the stomach and the proximal part of the duodenum.\r\n**Short gastric arteries**: Supply the fundus and upper part of the greater curvature of the stomach.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 307.","responses":[{"text":"Posterior gastric","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right gastro-omental","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Short gastric","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastroduodenal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left gastric","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13120,"text":"Which of the following artery is most likely to be eroded by an ulcer in the lesser curvature of the stomach?","explanation":"The artery most likely to be eroded by an ulcer in the lesser curvature of the stomach is the **Left gastric artery**.\r\n\r\nThe lesser curvature of the stomach is primarily supplied by the left gastric artery, which arises directly from the celiac trunk. An ulcer in this area would thus be in close proximity to this artery, posing a significant risk of hemorrhage if the ulcer perforates through the stomach wall and into the vessel.\r\n\r\n**Gastroduodenal artery**: Supplies the pyloric region of the stomach and the proximal duodenum.\r\n**Short gastric arteries**: Supply the fundus and upper part of the greater curvature of the stomach.\r\n**Splenic artery**: Supplies the spleen, and indirectly the greater curvature through short gastric arteries.\r\n**Inferior pancreaticoduodenal artery**: Supplies the pancreas and duodenum, not directly involved with the stomach's lesser curvature.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 105.","responses":[{"text":"Short gastric","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastroduodenol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Splenic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left gastric","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior pancreaticodudenol","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13122,"text":"Which of the following cells are present in the glands of the normal mucosa of the stomach?","explanation":"The glands of the normal mucosa of the stomach predominantly contain **Parietal cells**. These cells are responsible for the secretion of hydrochloric acid (HCl) and intrinsic factor, essential for vitamin B12 absorption. \r\n\r\n**Absorptive cells**: These cells are more common in the small intestine where nutrient absorption occurs.\r\n**Enterocytes**: Similar to absorptive cells, these are found mainly in the intestine and are specialized for absorption.\r\n**M cells**: These cells are generally found in the Peyer's patches of the ileum and are involved in antigen uptake.\r\n**Paneth cells**: These are found in the small intestine and are involved in secreting antimicrobial peptides.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2015: 310, 315-318.","responses":[{"text":"Parietal","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Enterocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Paneth","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Absorptive","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"M cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13123,"text":"The pain in the epigastric region in peptic ulcer disease is referred through which of the following nerves?","explanation":"The pain in the epigastric region due to peptic ulcer disease is referred through the **Greater splanchnic** nerve. This nerve is primarily responsible for carrying sympathetic fibers that originate from the thoracic spinal segments (T5-T9). It plays a key role in conveying pain and sensory information from the abdominal viscera, including the stomach, back to the central nervous system. In conditions such as peptic ulcer disease, activation of these sensory fibers leads to the perception of epigastric pain.\r\n\r\n**Vagus**: Though critical for parasympathetic control of the stomach, the vagus nerve is not primarily responsible for transmitting pain in peptic ulcer disease.\r\n**Lower intercostal**: These nerves serve the intercostal muscles and are not involved in gastric sensation.\r\n**Lesser splanchnic**: Also carries sympathetic fibers but is not the main conduit for epigastric pain in this context.\r\n**Gray rami communicans**: These are communicative branches between sympathetic and spinal nerves and are not responsible for transmitting this type of pain.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 480.","responses":[{"text":"Lesser splanchnic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Greater splanchnic","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lower intercostal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gray rami communicans","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vagus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13124,"text":"In a research paper, the following line is written: \"To assess the frequency of mood disorders among medical students of Karachi.\" Which one of the following options best describes the statement in this scenario?","explanation":"The statement \"To assess the frequency of mood disorders among medical students of Karachi\" is best described as an **Objective**. In research, the objective states what the researchers aim to accomplish in their study. It outlines the specific goals or tasks that the researchers will undertake to complete their investigation. The objective is usually straightforward and measurable, providing a clear framework for the study.\r\n\r\n**Operational definitions**: These are specific explanations of abstract concepts involved in the research but are not goals.\r\n**Hypothesis**: This is a tentative assumption made to test its logical or empirical consequences, not the purpose of the study.\r\n**Rationale**: This provides the reasoning behind why the research is being conducted but does not state what the research aims to accomplish.\r\n**Topic**: This would be the general subject of research but doesn't specify what the researchers intend to do.","reference":"Dow Lecture slides: Renal module, Subject: Community-medicine, Topic: Research methodologies, Sub-topic: Objectives.","responses":[{"text":"Hypothesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Topic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Objective","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Operational definitions","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rationale","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13126,"text":"A group of medical students submits the plan for their research project to the institutional board. This plan contains background, objectives, hypothesis, methodology, consent form, questionnaire, and references. Which one of the following options best defines this plan for research in this scenario?","explanation":"The plan submitted by the medical students is best defined as a **Synopsis**. In research, a synopsis is a brief summary that outlines the main points and methodology of a research project. It typically includes background information, objectives, hypothesis, methodology, consent forms, questionnaires, and references, serving as a comprehensive guide for the study. \r\n\r\n**Introduction**: Only provides background and rationale for the research.\r\n**Hypothesis**: Specifies what the study aims to prove or disprove but doesn't include methodology or other elements.\r\n**Abstract**: A short summary that is usually published along with a research paper but lacks detailed methodology.\r\n**Rationale**: Explains the reason for conducting the research but lacks specifics on methodology and other elements.","reference":"Betkerur J. Guidelines for writing a research project synopsis or protocol. Indian Journal of Dermatology, Venereology and Leprology. Published November 1, 2008. Accessed December 8, 2022. https://ijdvl.com/guidelines-for-writing-a-research-project-synopsis-or-protocol/","responses":[{"text":"Introduction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypothesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Abstract","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rationale","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Synopsis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13127,"text":"In a small study, 12 women with endometrial cancer and 12 women with no apparent disease are contacted and asked whether they have ever used estrogen. Each woman with cancer is matched by age, race, weight, and parity to a woman without the disease. Which one of the following options best describes the type of study design in this scenario?","explanation":"The described study is a **Case-control** study. In this type of study, researchers start with individuals who already have the disease (cases) and compare them to individuals without the disease (controls). Various exposures or risk factors, such as estrogen use in this scenario, are then assessed retrospectively. \r\n\r\n**Ecological**: Looks at populations, not individuals, to identify associations between exposures and outcomes.\r\n**Cross-sectional**: Measures exposure and disease status at the same point in time in a defined population.\r\n**Cohort**: Starts with a group of exposed and unexposed individuals and then prospectively follows them over time to assess the development of the disease.\r\n**Case report**: Describes the clinical course of a single patient or a small group of patients but does not involve comparison to controls.\r\n\r\nThe described study also features **Matching**, where each case is paired with a control that is similar in specific characteristics, thereby reducing confounding variables.","reference":"Dow Lecture slides: Gastrointestinal module, Subject: Community-medicine, Topic: Study design II, Sub-topic: Case-control studies.","responses":[{"text":"Cross-sectional","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Case-control","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cohort","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ecological","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Case report","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13128,"text":"In a clinical trial, neither participants nor investigator is aware of the group allocation and treatment received. Which one of the following options best describes the type of\r\nblinding in this scenario?","explanation":"**Double blinding** is the correct answer. In a double-blind clinical trial, both the participants and the investigators are unaware of the group allocations and treatments being administered. This minimizes bias and ensures that the results are as objective as possible.\r\n\r\n**Single blinding**: Only one party, either the participant or the investigator, is unaware of the group allocation.\r\n**Triple blinding**: Involves blinding of the participant, investigator, and also the data analysts.\r\n**Masking**: A general term that can refer to any level of blinding but does not specify how many parties are blinded.\r\n**No blinding**: Both participant and investigator are aware of group allocation and treatment, increasing the risk for bias.","reference":"David S, Khandhar PB. Double-blind study. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed December 8, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK546641/","responses":[{"text":"Triple blinding","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Double blinding","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Single blinding","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Masking","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"No blinding","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16000,"text":"Which of the following increases gastric acid secretion?","explanation":"**Duodenal alkalinity** is the correct answer. Gastric acid secretion is primarily regulated by neural, hormonal, and local mechanisms. Alkaline pH in the duodenum triggers a feedback mechanism that promotes gastric acid secretion to normalize the pH for optimal enzymatic activity.\r\n\r\n**Gastric acidity**: High gastric acidity usually inhibits further secretion of gastric acid via negative feedback.\r\n**H2 receptor antagonists**: These drugs block histamine receptors on parietal cells, thereby reducing gastric acid secretion.\r\n**Vagotomy**: Surgical severing of the vagus nerve reduces gastric acid secretion as it inhibits the parasympathetic stimulation of the stomach.\r\n**Duodenal acidity**: Acidic content in the duodenum inhibits gastric acid secretion through hormonal feedback mechanisms involving secretin.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 812-814.","responses":[{"text":"Duodenal alkalinity","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastric acidity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Duodenal acidity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"H2 receptor antagonists","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vagotomy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16001,"text":"The appendicular artery is a branch of which of the following arteries?","explanation":"The **Iliocolic artery** is the correct answer. It is a branch of the superior mesenteric artery and supplies the terminal ileum, cecum, and vermiform appendix. The appendicular artery is a branch of the iliocolic artery that specifically supplies the appendix.\r\n\r\n**Middle colic artery**: This artery supplies the transverse colon and is also a branch of the superior mesenteric artery.\r\n**Right colic artery**: Supplies the ascending colon; also a branch of the superior mesenteric artery.\r\n**Left colic artery**: Supplies the descending colon and is a branch of the inferior mesenteric artery.\r\n**Anterior cecal artery**: A branch of the iliocolic artery, but it does not supply the appendix directly.","reference":"Drake RL, Vogl W, Mitchell AWM, Gray H. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 3rd ed. Churchill Livingstone/Elsevier; 2015: 321.","responses":[{"text":"Iliocolic artery","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Right colic artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior cecal artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left colic artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Middle colic artery","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16002,"text":"Which of the following cells are present in the small intestinal epithelium?","explanation":"The **Paneth cells** are the correct answer; they are specialized cells located in the crypts of Lieberkühn at the base of the villi in the small intestine. Paneth cells have a crucial role in maintaining gut homeostasis and defense, as they secrete antimicrobial peptides like lysozyme and defensins.\r\n\r\n**Oxyntic cells**: Also known as parietal cells, these are found in the stomach and secrete hydrochloric acid.\r\n**Mucous neck cells**: These cells are located in the neck region of gastric glands in the stomach and secrete mucus.\r\n**Chief cells**: Found in the stomach, these cells secrete pepsinogen, a precursor of the enzyme pepsin.\r\n**Teniae coli cells**: Teniae coli are bands of smooth muscle in the colon; they are not epithelial cells.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 13th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2013: 312.","responses":[{"text":"Teniae coli cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chief cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mucous neck cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oxyntic cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Paneth cells","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16003,"text":"Cremasteric muscle is supplied by which of the following nerves?","explanation":"The **Cremasteric muscle** is supplied by the **Genital branch of the Genitofemoral nerve**. This nerve originates from the lumbar plexus and descends through the psoas major muscle before branching into its genital and femoral components. The genital branch specifically supplies the cremasteric muscle, allowing for the elevation of the testicle, which is an essential aspect of the cremasteric reflex.\r\n\r\n**Femoral nerve**: Primarily supplies the anterior compartment of the thigh and is not involved in the innervation of the cremasteric muscle.\r\n**Subcostal nerve**: Supplies the abdominal wall but does not innervate the cremasteric muscle.\r\n**Iliohypogastric nerve**: Innervates the abdominal wall and contributes to innervation of the iliac crest, but not the cremasteric muscle.\r\n**Ilioinguinal nerve**: Also innervates regions of the abdominal wall and genital region, but not the cremasteric muscle.","reference":"Drake RL, Vogl W, Mitchell AWM, Gray H. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 3rd ed. Churchill Livingstone/Elsevier; 2015: 401.","responses":[{"text":"Iliohypogastric nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Subcostal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ilioinguinal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Genital branch of genitofemoral","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Femoral nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16004,"text":"A histologist was looking at the slide of a gastrointestinal organ. The mucosa of the organ showed a number us folds with not-so-deep pits. The muscularis externa had three layers, inner oblique, middle circular, and outer longitudinal. Which organ can it be?","explanation":"The organ described is the **Stomach**. The stomach is unique in having three layers of muscularis externa: an inner oblique layer, a middle circular layer, and an outer longitudinal layer. This allows for the complex churning movements needed for mechanical digestion. The mucosa of the stomach contains folds called rugae and relatively shallow gastric pits, which differentiate it from other gastrointestinal organs.\r\n\r\n**Liver**: Does not have a mucosa or muscularis externa as it is not a part of the gastrointestinal tract.\r\n**Gallbladder**: Characterized by a simple columnar epithelium and lacks the three muscular layers.\r\n**Duodenum**: Part of the small intestine, has villi and crypts of Lieberkühn but lacks the three muscular layers.\r\n**Pancreas**: An exocrine and endocrine gland, lacking the described layers.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 13th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2013: 309.","responses":[{"text":"Gallbladder","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Liver","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stomach","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pancreas","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Duodenum","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16005,"text":"Amino acids that are converted to acetyl-CoA cannot be used for gluconeogenesis because acetyl-coA cannot be converted to pyruvate. Which amino acids are these?","explanation":"The correct answer is **Ketogenic** amino acids. These amino acids can be metabolized to acetyl-CoA or its precursors, such as acetoacetate, but they cannot be converted back to pyruvate or any other gluconeogenic intermediates. As a result, they cannot be used for gluconeogenesis. Ketogenic amino acids include leucine and lysine. Some amino acids like phenylalanine, tryptophan, and isoleucine are both ketogenic and glucogenic, meaning they can yield both acetyl-CoA and gluconeogenic precursors.\r\n\r\n**Essential**: Refers to amino acids that must be obtained from the diet, but not all essential amino acids are ketogenic.\r\n**Semi-essential**: These amino acids can be synthesized but are also required in the diet. Their metabolic fate doesn't necessarily make them ketogenic.\r\n**Glucogenic**: These amino acids can be converted to gluconeogenic intermediates.\r\n**Non-essential**: These amino acids can be synthesized by the body but are not necessarily ketogenic.","reference":"Murray RK, Victor WR, Bender D, Kathleen MB, Weil PA, Kennelly PJ. Harper’s Illustrated Biochemistry. 28th ed. McGraw-Hill Professional; 2009: 231-232.","responses":[{"text":"Ketogenic","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Semi-essential","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Non-essential","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Essential","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucogenic","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16006,"text":"A 53-year-old male came to the emergency department due to marked hematemesis for the last three hours. On examination, he had a distended abdomen and fluid wave. What is the patient likely suffering from?","explanation":"The correct answer is **Cirrhosis**. The symptoms described, including marked hematemesis (vomiting blood) and fluid wave indicating abdominal distension, commonly point to end-stage liver disease, likely cirrhosis. Hematemesis could be due to esophageal varices, a complication of portal hypertension commonly seen in cirrhosis. Ascites (fluid accumulation in the abdominal cavity) may also present as abdominal distension and is another complication of cirrhosis.\r\n\r\n**Massive hepatic necrosis**: This condition would lead to acute liver failure rather than chronic symptoms like ascites and esophageal varices.\r\n**Cholangiocarcinoma**: While this cancer can cause liver dysfunction, it is not typically associated with hematemesis and ascites.\r\n**HAV infection**: Hepatitis A is an acute infection and doesn't usually cause chronic liver disease.\r\n**Fatty liver**: Isolated fatty liver typically does not result in severe complications like hematemesis.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 826-827.","responses":[{"text":"Massive hepatic necrosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HAV infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cholangiocarcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cirrhosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Fatty liver","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16007,"text":"Which of the following is a distinguishing feature of the gallbladder?","explanation":"The correct answer is **No submucosa**. Unlike many other parts of the gastrointestinal system, the gallbladder lacks a submucosa. The wall of the gallbladder primarily consists of a mucosa lined by simple columnar epithelium, a muscularis layer, and a serosa.\r\n\r\n**Simple cuboidal epithelium in mucosa**: The gallbladder mucosa is actually lined by simple columnar epithelium, not cuboidal.\r\n**Smooth mucosa**: The gallbladder mucosa is often folded, forming rugae, especially when the gallbladder is contracted.\r\n**Thick submucosa**: The gallbladder lacks a submucosa, making this statement incorrect.\r\n**Thick muscularis**: While the gallbladder does have a muscularis layer, it's not particularly thick compared to some other GI organs.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 13th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2013: 339.","responses":[{"text":"Thick muscularis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Smooth mucosa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"No submucosa","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Simple cuboidal epithelium in mucosa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thick submucosa","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16070,"text":"Which of the following is the first identified case in a location?","explanation":"The correct answer is **Index case**. The index case is the first identified case in a particular outbreak, epidemic, or pandemic and serves as a point of reference for the spread of the disease. Identification of the index case helps epidemiologists trace the source and the pattern of transmission, which can be critical for implementing effective containment strategies.\r\n\r\n**Primordial case**: This term is not commonly used in epidemiology for describing the first case in a location.\r\n**Primary case**: Refers to a case that is the source of transmission to secondary cases but is not necessarily the first identified case.\r\n**Secondary case**: These are cases that arise from exposure to the primary case.\r\n**Tertiary case**: These cases arise from exposure to secondary cases.","reference":"Index case - an overview | sciencedirect topics. Accessed June 6, 2023. https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/mathematics/index-case","responses":[{"text":"Tertiary case","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Primordial case","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Index case","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Secondary case","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Primary case","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16071,"text":"Which hormone increases pancreatic enzymatic secretion, decreases gastric emptying, and is secreted due to the presence of fatty acids and protein breakdown products in the duodenum?","explanation":"The correct answer is **Cholecystokinin (CCK)**. Cholecystokinin is released in response to the presence of fatty acids and protein breakdown products in the duodenum. It plays a crucial role in the digestive process by stimulating the pancreatic acinar cells to secrete digestive enzymes into the pancreatic duct, thereby aiding in the digestion of proteins and fats. Furthermore, CCK slows down gastric emptying to allow time for these nutrients to be digested.\r\n\r\n**Somatostatin** inhibits the secretion of several gastrointestinal hormones but doesn't stimulate pancreatic enzymatic secretion.\r\n**Secretin** primarily triggers bicarbonate secretion from the pancreas, not enzymes.\r\n**Gastrin** stimulates gastric acid secretion and is not primarily responsible for pancreatic enzymatic secretion.\r\n**Motilin** is mainly involved in regulating gastrointestinal motility.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 802, 817.","responses":[{"text":"Gastrin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Somatostatin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Motilin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Secretin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cholecystokinin","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16072,"text":"Acetyl-CoA is used in the synthesis of cholesterol. Which of the following is the rate-limiting step for cholesterol synthesis?","explanation":"The correct answer is **Synthesis of mevalonate**. The rate-limiting step for cholesterol synthesis is the conversion of 3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-CoA (HMG-CoA) to mevalonate, catalyzed by the enzyme HMG-CoA reductase. This step is crucial for the regulation of cholesterol biosynthesis and is the target for cholesterol-lowering drugs like statins.\r\n\r\nSynthesis of farnesyl and squalene are downstream steps in the pathway.\r\nSynthesis of HMG-CoA is an earlier step but is not rate-limiting.\r\nSynthesis of isopentenyl pyrophosphate (IPP) is also downstream and not rate-limiting.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 221.","responses":[{"text":"Synthesis of farnesyl","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Synthesis of mevalonate","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Synthesis of HMG-CoA","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Synthesis of squalene","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Synthesis of isopentenyl pyrophosphate (IPP)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16073,"text":"A 40-year-old male patient visits the outpatient department with complaints of epigastric pain. The pain is relieved by meals and antacids. Gastric analysis shows increased basal and active acid secretion. Which of the following causes gastric hypersecretion?","explanation":"The correct answer is **Gastrin**. Gastrin is a hormone produced by the G cells in the stomach antrum and duodenum. It stimulates the parietal cells in the stomach lining to secrete hydrochloric acid. In conditions such as Zollinger-Ellison syndrome, there is a hypersecretion of gastrin, leading to excessive acid production, epigastric pain, and symptoms that are relieved by meals and antacids.\r\n\r\nSecretin primarily stimulates the pancreas and inhibits gastric acid secretion.\r\nSomatostatin is an inhibitory hormone that decreases gastric acid secretion.\r\nEnterogastrone slows down the activity of the stomach but is not involved in acid hypersecretion.\r\nVasoactive intestinal peptide (VIP) generally stimulates intestinal secretion and smooth muscle relaxation but not gastric acid secretion.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 770-771, 773.","responses":[{"text":"Vasoactive intestinal peptide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Secretin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastrin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Somatostatin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Enterogastrone","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16074,"text":"During the early stages of fasting, what maintains a steady level of glucose after dietary glucose runs out?","explanation":"The correct answer is **Hepatic glycogenolysis**. During the early stages of fasting, when dietary glucose is no longer available, the liver maintains blood glucose levels primarily through the breakdown of glycogen stored in the liver, a process known as hepatic glycogenolysis. Enzymes cleave glucose units from glycogen to be released into the bloodstream.\r\n\r\nHepatic gluconeogenesis becomes more significant in prolonged fasting but is not the primary source in the early stages.\r\nHepatic ketogenesis provides alternative fuels like ketone bodies, but it doesn't maintain glucose levels.\r\nHepatic fatty acid oxidation is involved in energy production but does not produce glucose.\r\nHepatic glycolysis is the breakdown of glucose, not its production.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 851.","responses":[{"text":"Hepatic glycogenolysis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatic fatty acid oxidation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatic ketogenesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatic glycolysis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatic gluconeogenesis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16080,"text":"MMA fighter got punched in the abdomen and injured his rectus abdominis muscle. Which of the following nerves supply this muscle?","explanation":"The correct answer is **Lower six thoracic** nerves. The rectus abdominis muscle is supplied by the lower six thoracic spinal nerves, specifically T7-T12. These nerves carry both motor and sensory fibers. A strong punch in the abdomen can cause trauma to the muscle and may affect these thoracic nerves.\r\n\r\nCervical plexus doesn't innervate abdominal muscles; it mainly supplies the neck.\r\n\"Lowest thoracic\" could imply only T12, which is not sufficient to supply the entire rectus abdominis.\r\nIlioinguinal nerve is more involved in the sensory innervation of the inguinal and pubic regions.\r\nUpper six thoracic nerves are not involved in the innervation of the rectus abdominis; they mainly supply structures in the thorax.","reference":"Drake RL, Vogl W, Mitchell AWM, Gray H. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 3rd ed. Churchill Livingstone/Elsevier; 2015: 286.","responses":[{"text":"Lowest thoracic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cervical plexus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lower six thoracic","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Upper six thoracic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ilioinguinal","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16081,"text":"Which of the following structures forms the left boundary of the lesser sac when viewing a transverse section image of the peritoneal cavity?","explanation":"The correct answer is **Splenorenal ligament**. In a transverse section of the peritoneal cavity, the splenorenal ligament forms the left boundary of the lesser sac, also known as the omental bursa. The splenorenal ligament connects the spleen to the posterior abdominal wall and the left kidney. \r\n\r\nLesser omentum forms the anterior boundary of the lesser sac.\r\nLeft kidney is located posteriorly and does not directly form a boundary of the lesser sac.\r\nOmental foramen is the opening that connects the lesser sac to the greater sac; it doesn't form a boundary.\r\nLiver is anterior to the lesser sac and forms its superior and right boundaries.","reference":"Drake RL, Vogl W, Mitchell AWM, Gray H. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 3rd ed. Churchill Livingstone/Elsevier; 2015: 305, 309.","responses":[{"text":"Omental foramen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Splenorenal ligament","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lesser omentum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Liver","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left kidney","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16082,"text":"Which of the following are present in the space of Disse?","explanation":"The correct answer is **Hepatic stellate cells**. The space of Disse, also known as the perisinusoidal space, is located between the sinusoidal endothelial cells and the hepatocytes in the liver. It contains hepatic stellate cells, which play a role in vitamin A storage and are involved in liver fibrosis when activated.\r\n\r\nCholangiocytes are the epithelial cells of the bile ducts, not present in the space of Disse.\r\nEndothelial cells line the sinusoids but are not located within the space of Disse.\r\nKupffer cells are liver macrophages found within the lumen of the liver sinusoids, not in the space of Disse.\r\nHepatic veins are large vessels that collect blood from the central veins of the liver lobules; they are not components of the space of Disse.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 13th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2015: 333-334.","responses":[{"text":"Cholangiocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Kupffer cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatic veins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endothelial cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatic stellate cells","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16083,"text":"Which of the following is true for marasmus?","explanation":"The correct answer is **Lack of calorie more than protein**. Marasmus is a form of severe malnutrition characterized by energy deficiency, leading primarily to weight loss and muscle wasting. Unlike kwashiorkor, where protein deficiency is more pronounced, marasmus primarily involves a caloric deficiency. \r\n\r\nLack of protein more than calorie describes kwashiorkor, not marasmus.\r\nExcessive body weight is opposite to the weight loss seen in marasmus.\r\nMalnutrition but no anemia is not specific; marasmus can indeed be associated with anemia due to overall nutrient deficiencies.\r\nToo much edema is characteristic of kwashiorkor, which results from protein deficiency, not marasmus.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 369.","responses":[{"text":"Too much edema","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Malnutrition but no anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lack of protein more than calorie","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lack of calorie more than protein","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Excessive body weight","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16084,"text":"The hepatic artery proper is a branch of the common hepatic artery. Which of the following structures does it pass through before entering the liver?","explanation":"The correct answer is **Hepatoduodenal ligament**. The hepatic artery proper, a branch of the common hepatic artery, passes through the hepatoduodenal ligament before entering the liver. This ligament forms the anterior boundary of the omental foramen and contains not only the hepatic artery proper but also the portal vein and the common bile duct, collectively forming the portal triad.\r\n\r\nThe hepatogastric ligament connects the liver to the lesser curvature of the stomach and does not contain the hepatic artery proper.\r\nThe splenorenal and gastrosplenic ligaments are associated with the spleen, not the liver or hepatic artery proper.\r\nThe hepatophrenic ligament connects the liver to the diaphragm and also does not contain the hepatic artery proper.","reference":"Drake RL, Vogl W, Mitchell AWM, Gray H. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 3rd ed. Churchill Livingstone/Elsevier; 2015: 307.","responses":[{"text":"Splenorenal ligament","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatophrenic ligament","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatoduodenal ligament","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatogastric ligament","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastrosplenic ligament","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16085,"text":"The coronary ligament attaches the liver to which of the following structures?","explanation":"The correct answer is **Diaphragm**. The coronary ligament is a peritoneal fold that attaches the liver to the undersurface of the diaphragm. It's an extension of the peritoneum and helps to stabilize the liver's position within the abdominal cavity.\r\n\r\nThe liver is not directly attached to the pancreas, transverse colon, first part of the duodenum, or left suprarenal gland by the coronary ligament.\r\nThe pancreas is located inferior and posterior to the liver but is not directly connected by the coronary ligament.\r\nThe transverse colon is inferior to the liver and has no direct attachment via the coronary ligament.\r\nThe first part of the duodenum and the left suprarenal gland are also not directly attached to the liver via the coronary ligament.","reference":"Drake RL, Vogl W, Mitchell AWM, Gray H. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 3rd ed. Churchill Livingstone/Elsevier; 2015: 331.","responses":[{"text":"First part of duodenum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pancreas","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left suprarenal gland","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transverse colon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diaphragm","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16086,"text":"In which part of the gastrointestinal tract is most of the vitamin b12 is absorbed?","explanation":"The correct answer is **Ileum**. Most of the vitamin B12 is absorbed in the terminal ileum. In the stomach, vitamin B12 is released from dietary proteins and then binds to intrinsic factor, a glycoprotein secreted by the parietal cells. This B12-intrinsic factor complex travels through the small intestine and is specifically absorbed by receptor-mediated endocytosis in the ileum. \r\n\r\nThe stomach is where vitamin B12 is liberated from food but not where it is absorbed.\r\nThe colon does not play a role in vitamin B12 absorption.\r\nThe jejunum and duodenum are not the primary sites for vitamin B12 absorption; instead, they are more involved in the absorption of other nutrients like carbohydrates, proteins, and fats.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 890.","responses":[{"text":"Stomach","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Duodenum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ileum","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Jejunum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Colon","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16095,"text":"How does the rectum differ from the descending colon histologically?","explanation":"The correct answer is **It has a comparatively smooth muscularis externa**. Histologically, the muscularis externa of the rectum is notably smoother compared to that of the descending colon. In the colon, the muscularis externa is organized into three distinct bands of longitudinal muscle known as taeniae coli. These bands are absent in the rectum, where the muscularis externa is more uniform and smooth.\r\n\r\nBoth the rectum and descending colon have a muscularis mucosa and submucosa, essential layers for their respective functions.\r\nPeyer's patches are primarily located in the ileum and are not a key differentiating factor between the rectum and the descending colon.\r\nNeither the rectum nor the descending colon is completely covered by adventitia; they both have areas where they are covered by serosa instead.","reference":"Laiq Hussain Siddiqui. Medical Histology Text And Atlas. 6th ed. Paramount; 2019: 189.","responses":[{"text":"It lacks payers patches","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It has a comparatively smooth muscularis externa","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"It has no submucosa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is completely covered by adventitia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It has no muscularis mucosa","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16096,"text":"Gallbladder releases its secretion in a structure present between its neck and the cystic duct. Which of the following structures matches this description?","explanation":"The correct answer is **Hartman's pouch**. Hartman's pouch is a small outpouching of the gallbladder located between the neck of the gallbladder and the cystic duct. This region can sometimes accumulate gallstones and is the site where bile is often temporarily stored before being released into the cystic duct.\r\n\r\nThe common hepatic duct is a duct that joins with the cystic duct to form the common bile duct, but it is not situated between the gallbladder neck and the cystic duct.\r\nThe fundus is the distal end of the gallbladder and is not between its neck and the cystic duct.\r\nThe major duodenal papilla is the site where the common bile duct empties into the duodenum, unrelated to the gallbladder neck and cystic duct.\r\nThe body of the stomach is an unrelated structure and not involved in gallbladder secretion.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 511-512.","responses":[{"text":"Major duodenal papilla","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hartman's pouch","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Body of stomach","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Common hepatic duct","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fundus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16097,"text":"A small triangular muscle is located anterior to the lower part of the rectus abdominis muscle within the rectus sheath and attached to the pubic symphysis and the pubic crest. It tenses the linea alba and is often absent in some people. Which of the following muscles matches this description?","explanation":"The correct answer is **Pyramidalis**. The pyramidalis muscle is a small, triangular muscle situated anterior to the lower part of the rectus abdominis muscle, within the rectus sheath. It originates from the pubic symphysis and the pubic crest and inserts into the linea alba. Its primary function is to tense the linea alba, although its absence in some individuals suggests that it is not essential for abdominal wall integrity or function. \r\n\r\nPsoas is a major muscle in the lumbar region and not anterior to the rectus abdominis.\r\nTransversalis fascia is not a muscle but a layer of fascia in the abdominal wall.\r\nInternal and external obliques are lateral abdominal muscles and do not fit the description of being anterior to the lower part of the rectus abdominis and often","reference":"Drake RL, Vogl W, Mitchell AWM, Gray H. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 3rd ed. Churchill Livingstone/Elsevier; 2015: 286-287.","responses":[{"text":"External oblique","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Psoas","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Internal oblique","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transversalis facia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pyramidalis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16098,"text":"The posterior boundary of the omental foramen or foramen of Winslow is formed by which structure?","explanation":"The correct answer is **Peritoneum of inferior vena cava**. The omental foramen, also known as the foramen of Winslow, is an opening that connects the greater sac and lesser sac in the abdominal cavity. The posterior boundary of this foramen is formed by the peritoneum covering the inferior vena cava. \r\n\r\nThe peritoneum of the hepatoduodenal ligament and hepatic portal vein are actually components of the anterior boundary of the omental foramen.\r\nThe peritoneum of the liver is superiorly related but does not form the posterior boundary.\r\nThe peritoneum of the duodenum is inferiorly related and is not involved in the formation of this foramen's posterior boundary.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 444.","responses":[{"text":"Peritoneum of duodenum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Peritoneum of hepatoduodenal ligament","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Peritoneum of inferior vena cava","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatic portal vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Peritoneum of liver","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16099,"text":"Considering its origin at the pubic crest, pubic tubercle, and pubic symphysis, and its insertion on the costal cartilages, at which level of the ribs does the rectus abdominis muscle insert?","explanation":"The correct answer is **V-VII**. The rectus abdominis muscle originates from the pubic crest, pubic tubercle, and pubic symphysis and inserts on the costal cartilages of the fifth, sixth, and seventh ribs (V-VII). This muscle is a key component of the anterior abdominal wall and plays a crucial role in flexing the trunk.","reference":"Drake RL, Vogl W, Mitchell AWM, Gray H. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 3rd ed. Churchill Livingstone/Elsevier; 2015: 286.","responses":[{"text":"VIII-X","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"V-VII","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"VII-IX","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"V-XI","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"V-IX","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16100,"text":"During inflammation which of the following chemicals are responsible for causing pain?","explanation":"The correct answer is **Bradykinin and prostaglandins**. During inflammation, pain is mainly mediated by chemical mediators like bradykinin and prostaglandins. Bradykinin acts on sensory nerve endings to induce the sensation of pain. Prostaglandins, synthesized from arachidonic acid via the cyclooxygenase pathway, sensitize pain receptors and augment the effects of other mediators like bradykinin.\r\n\r\nInterleukins and tumor necrosis factor are primarily involved in the regulation of the immune response but are not directly responsible for pain.\r\nAcetylcholine and dopamine are involved in neuromuscular junction and mood regulation, not pain during inflammation.\r\nHistamine and serotonin are innvolved in vasodilation and mood regulation, not directly responsible for causing pain.\r\nNitric oxide is a vasodilator, and leukotrienes are involved in the immune response, not directly in pain.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 92.","responses":[{"text":"Interleukins and tumor necrosis factor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bradykinin and prostaglandins","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Histamine and serotonin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nitric oxide and leukotrienes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acetylcholine and dopamine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16101,"text":"Gallbladder pain is referred to the right infrascapsular region. It receives its innervation from which nerve roots?","explanation":"Gallbladder pain is primarily referred to the right infrascapsular region due to the **phrenic nerve innervation** of the gallbladder, which has roots in **C3-C5** spinal levels. The C3-C5 nerve roots contribute to the formation of the phrenic nerve, which provides sensory innervation to the gallbladder. When the gallbladder is irritated or inflamed, such as in cases of cholecystitis, the pain is sensed by these nerve fibers and referred to the area where these nerve roots also provide cutaneous innervation.","reference":"Drake RL, Vogl W, Mitchell AWM, Gray H. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 3rd ed. Churchill Livingstone/Elsevier; 2015: 341.","responses":[{"text":"C3-C5","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"T12-L2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"T11-L1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"T7-T9","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"L1-S2","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16102,"text":"Which germ layer gives rise to muscularis externa of the gut?","explanation":"The correct answer is **Mesoderm**. The muscularis externa of the gut is derived from the mesoderm. Specifically, it originates from the splanchnic mesoderm surrounding the primitive gut tube during embryogenesis. This layer gives rise to the smooth muscle that forms the muscularis externa, responsible for the peristaltic movements of the gastrointestinal tract.\r\n\r\nThe ectoderm primarily gives rise to structures like the skin and nervous system but not the muscularis externa of the gut.\r\nNeural tube cells are precursors to the central nervous system, not the muscular layers of the gut.\r\nNeural crest cells contribute to the enteric nervous system but are not responsible for forming the muscularis externa.\r\nThe endoderm gives rise to the epithelial lining of the gut, not the muscularis externa.","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2016: 52.","responses":[{"text":"Mesoderm","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Endoderm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ectoderm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neural crest cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neural tube","correct":false,"visible":false}]}
]

